Here's the xUnit equivalent:

**Per-test setup/teardown** → constructor + `IDisposable`
**One-time setup/teardown** → `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture class

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Constructor/Dispose replace [SetUp] / [TearDown]
public class CustomerRepositoryTests
    : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | fixture's `Dispose` |
| `[SetUp]` | test class constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

The fixture is instantiated once and shared across all tests in the class. xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/Dispose naturally gives you per-test setup/teardown. If your teardown is async, implement `IAsyncDisposable.DisposeAsync` instead.
